{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567800"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:07:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:07:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19389"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19389"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.28,0.09,0.3,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12116"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98432"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12116"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19389"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80876"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5457"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"12776"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28650"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33214"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33287"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44999"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98432"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic seeking pre-travel advice. He is planning a three-month backpacking trip through central Africa, including Uganda and Tanzania. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. He has heard about African Sleeping Sickness and is concerned about contracting the infection during his travels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most effective strategy to prevent African trypanosomiasis infection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Weekly prophylactic medication","Using mosquito nets while sleeping","Drinking only bottled water","Wearing light-coloured, long-sleeved clothing","Using DEET-containing insect repellent"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAfrican trypanosomiasis (sleeping sickness) is caused by \u003Cem\u003ETrypanosoma brucei\u003C/em\u003E parasites transmitted through the bite of infected tsetse flies typically endemic in sub-Sahara Africa.  American trypanosomiasis (Chagas disease) is a separate parasitic infection in Latin America.  Patients present with haemolymphatic symptoms (fever, lymphadenopathy, pruritis and arthralgia), neurological disturbances, sleep disorders and death in untreated cases. Serological testing and lumbar puncture can be done to detect the disease.  Treatment is with fexinidazole for 10 days.  Patients travelling to agricultural areas, or rural areas of fishing or hunting should be aware of the symptoms and seek medical treatment promptly as early treatment is crucial for better outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWearing light-coloured, long-sleeved clothing\u003C/strong\u003E is the most effective prevention strategy. Tsetse flies are attracted to dark and bright colours, particularly blue and black. Long-sleeved shirts and long trousers in neutral colours provide a physical barrier against bites. The flies can bite through thin fabric, so clothing should be medium weight.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUsing DEET-containing insect repellent\u003C/strong\u003E is not particularly effective against tsetse flies. While DEET-containing repellents offer some protection, tsetse flies are less deterred by these repellents compared to mosquitoes. Repellents should be used as a supplementary measure rather than the primary prevention strategy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no \u003Cstrong\u003Eweekly prophylactic medication\u003C/strong\u003E available for African trypanosomiasis prevention, unlike malaria which has several prophylactic options.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUsing mosquito nets\u003C/strong\u003E while sleeping would not be effective as tsetse flies do not typically bite at night and are strong enough to penetrate standard mosquito nets.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrinking only bottled water\u003C/strong\u003E would not prevent trypanosomiasis as it is not transmitted through contaminated water. This measure would help prevent other travel-related illnesses such as traveller\u0027s diarrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional preventive measures include avoiding bushes during the heat of the day where tsetse flies rest, and travelling in air-conditioned vehicles when possible. Mother-to child transmission can also occur or less commonly from contaminated needles in laboratories.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["African trypanosomiasis is transmitted by the tsetse fly, which is active during daylight hours and attracted to bright colours and movement.","Preventive measures focus on avoiding tsetse fly bites through appropriate clothing and insect repellent use.","There is no vaccine or prophylactic medication available for African trypanosomiasis."],"references":["Kennedy PGE. Update on human African trypanosomiasis (sleeping sickness). J Neurol. 2019; 66:2334-337","World Health Organization. Trypanosomiasis, Human African (sleeping sickness) [Internet]. WHO. World Health Organization: WHO; 2023. Available from: https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/trypanosomiasis-human-african-(sleeping-sickness)","Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Preventing sleeping sickness. [Internet]. Atlanta (GA): Centers for Disease Control and Prevention; 2024 Mar 25. Available from: https://www.cdc.gov/sleeping-sickness/prevention/index.html","Lejon V, Lindner AK, Franco JR. Human African trypanosomiasis. Lancet 2025; 405: 937\u201350."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80876"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19389"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80876"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-13T14:56:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-13T14:56:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12116"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98432"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"38","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/38"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data